      <abstract>Minnie E. Carter was born in Redding, Connecticut on June 13, 1886. She was a member
        of the First Congregational Church of Bethel, participating in the choir, the Sunshine
        Society, and was a Sunday School teacher. In 1916, Minnie would leave the United States and
        live in South Africa at the Inanda Seminary. Minnie would remain at Inanda Seminary from
        1916 through her retirement in 1957.While at Inanda, Minnie would teach on a variety of
        subjects including the Bible, English, Mathematics, Biology, and serve as a substitute
        teacher as needed. Minnie would return to the United States permanently in 1957 following
        her retirement. After returning, she served as a deaconess for the First Congregational
        Church in Bethel, organized prayer groups, and visited members of the community who
        typically stayed in their homes. Minnie E. Carter died on September 29th, 1974. This
        collection contains various subject files and photographs from Minnie Carter's time working
        for the Inanda Seminary in South Africa under the American Board of Commissioners for
        Foreign Missions from 1917-1957.</abstract>
