    <bioghist>
      <head>Biographical Information</head>
      <p>Minnie E. Carter was born in Redding, Connecticut on June 13, 1886. Her family moved to
        Bethel, Connecticut when she was 3. She graduated as a valedictorian at Bethel High School
        in 1904 and also graduated from Danbury Normal School in 1906. She was a member of the First
        Congregational Church of Bethel, participating in the choir, the Sunshine Society, and was a
        Sunday School teacher.</p>
      <p>Minnie taught elementary grades from 1906 to 1915 in Bridgewater, Bethel, and Stamford,
        Connecticut. From 1915 to 1916, she attended the New York Biblical Seminary in New York
        City. In May of 1915, Minnie and 54 other missionaries from the American Board of
        Commissioners for Foreign Missions (ABCFM) participated in a Farewell Service at the Second
        Congregational Church in Dorchester. A year later, she leaves the United States to live in
        South Africa at the Inanda Seminary. </p>
      <p>The Inanda Seminary is an all-girls school located about 20 miles north of the city of
        Durban. The school was founded by Daniel and Lucy Lindley in 1869 and continues to operate
        as of 2026. Minnie would remain at Inanda Seminary from 1916 through her retirement in 1957,
        excluding some furloughs that took place in 1926, 1938, and 1949. While at Inanda, Minnie
        would teach on a variety of subjects including the Bible, English, Mathematics, Biology, and
        serve as a substitute teacher as needed. She also supervised a number of extracurricular
        archivists like drama and sports, introduced a library in 1927, and organized Sunday School
        training for students. After serving as interim principle from 1928-1929, she was the head
        teacher from 1930-1948.</p>
      <p>Minnie would return to the United States permanently in 1957 following her retirement.
        After returning, she served as a deaconess for the First Congregational Church in Bethel,
        organized prayer groups, and visited members of the community who typically stayed in their
        homes. Minnie E. Carter died on September 29th, 1974.</p>
    </bioghist>
    <scopecontent>
      <head>Scope and Contents</head>
      <p>This collection contains various subject files and photographs from Minnie Carter's time
        working for the Inanda Seminary in South Africa under the American Board of Commissioners
        for Foreign Missions from 1917-1957. Additional materials from after she returned to the
        United States are also included.</p>
    </scopecontent>
    <arrangement>
      <head>Arrangement</head>
      <p>The collection is divided into two series and further arranged chronologically by start
        date. When possible, material retains the folder titles as they were when the collection was
        donated.</p>
      <p><emph render="bold">Series 1:</emph> Subject files, 1869, 1911-1986</p>
      <p><emph render="bold">Series 2:</emph> Photographs, undated</p>
    </arrangement>
